<br>
October 29, 1997- American members of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) inspection team are expelled from Iraq, only to return November 20. <br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
January 13, 1998 - Iraq temporarily withdraws cooperation, complaining the inspection team has a disproportionate share of U.S. and British members. A week later inspectors are refused access to presidential sites.<br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
February 20-23, 1998 - U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan secures full Iraqi cooperation and access for inspectors.<br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
October 31, 1998 - Iraq ceases cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission but allows inspections to resume 14 days later.<br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
December 16, 1998 - The U.N. Special Commission removes all staff from Iraq after inspectors conclude Iraq is not fully cooperating.<br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
December 17, 1999 - The United Nations replaces the U.N. Special Commission with the U.N. Monitoring Verification and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC). Iraq rejects the resolution.<br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
March 1, 2000 - Hans Blix becomes executive chairman of the U.N. Monitoring Verification and Inspection Commission.<br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
November 2000 - Iraq rejects new weapons inspections proposals.<br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
August 1, 2002 - In a letter from the Iraqi government to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Hans Blix is invited to Iraq for discussions on disarmament issues.<br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
August 6, 2002 - Secretary-General Kofi Annan writes to the Iraqis, pointing out that their proposal is at odds with U.N. resolutions and asking that Iraq accept inspections.<br>
Source: AP<br>
<br>
September 12, 2002 - In an attempt to build a global coalition for action against Iraq, President Bush pushes for a new U.N. Security Council resolution and for action within weeks but doesn't lay down any deadlines for returning weapons inspectors to the country.<br>
<br>
President Bush tells the United Nations it must rid the world of Iraq's biological, chemical and nuclear arsenals, or stand aside as the United States acts.<br>
Source: AP <br>
<br>
September 16, 2002 - Iraq unconditionally accepts the return of U.N. weapons inspectors.<br>
Source: AP <br>
<br>
There in easy to read tasty little bites is 4 years(5, but we're excluding 97) of Iraq not living up to its end of Res. 1441 ending only after GW says he's ready to bomb them back to the stone age.<br>
